          "field_id": "a_phyllodes_tumor_is_regarded_as_malignant_when_there_are_malignant_heterologous_elements_even_when_",
          "label": "A phyllodes tumor is regarded as malignant when there are malignant heterologous elements, even when not all of the other histological features of malignancy are present. This rule does not apply if the only heterologous element is well differentiated liposarcoma. In the breast, those tumors usually lack MDM2 and CDK4 amplifications and have a low metastatic risk. A diagnosis of malignant phyllodes tumor should therefore not be based solely on the presence of well-differentiated liposarcoma without all of the other histologic features of malignancy.",
